title: Who should not use Repatha?
question: Who should not use Repatha (evolocumab)?
answer: Do not use Repatha if you are allergic to evolocumab or to any of the ingredients in Repatha. Seek emergency help for signs of a serious allergic reaction (e.g., trouble breathing or swallowing, hives, rash or itching, swelling of the face, lips, tongue, throat, or arms).

title: What should I tell my healthcare provider before using Repatha?
question: What should I tell my healthcare provider before using Repatha?
answer: Tell your healthcare provider about all your medical conditions and all the medicines, vitamins, and herbal supplements you take. Mention if you are allergic to rubber or latex, are pregnant or plan to become pregnant, or are breastfeeding or plan to breastfeed.

title: Does Repatha contain latex?
question: Does Repatha contain latex?
answer: Some Repatha presentations (prefilled single-dose SureClick autoinjectors and prefilled single-dose syringes) may contain dry natural rubber (a derivative of latex) in the needle cover; others are not made with natural rubber latex. The carton and "Instructions for Use" indicate whether the device contains dry natural rubber. The single-dose Pushtronex system is not made with natural rubber latex.

title: Possible side effects of Repatha
question: What are the possible side effects of Repatha?
answer: Serious allergic reactions can occur. Stop taking Repatha and seek help if you have trouble breathing or swallowing, hives, rash or itching, or swelling of the face, lips, tongue, throat, or arms. The most common side effects include: runny nose, sore throat, symptoms of the common cold, flu or flu-like symptoms, back pain, high blood sugar levels (diabetes), and redness, pain, or bruising at the injection site.
